d had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Mautravers was born about 1292, in Dorset, England, United Kingdom, his father, Sir John Mautravers, was 55 and his mother, Joan of Woolcombe, was 54. He married Lucy de Brewes about 1309, in Bramber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died before 1321."},"et":{"about 1292–before 1321":"umbes 1292–enne 1321","1262–Female":"1262–Surnud","1264–1330":"1264–1330","1266–1341":"1266–1341","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1292–1321":"1292–1321","1293–Female":"1293–Surnud","1310–1353":"1310–1353","1238–1297":"1238–1297","1239–1297":"1239–1297","about 1292":"umbes 1292","before 1321":"enne 1321","1297":"1297","1341":"1341","1330":"1330","1264":"1264","1262":"1262","1260":"1260","1293":"1293","1292":"1292","about 1309":"umbes 1309","1239":"1239","1238":"1238","1268":"1268","1310":"1310","1321":"1321","1266":"1266","28 February 1297":"28. veebruar 1297","1353":"1353","about 1310":"umbes 1310","Lychet Maltravers, Dorset, England":"Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bramber,Sussex,England":"Bramber, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Dorset, England":"Dorset, England","Meriden, Warwickshire, England":"Meriden, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1292–before 1321":"noin 1292–ennen vuotta 1321","1262–Female":"1262–Kuollut","1264–1330":"1264–1330","1266–1341":"1266–1